                        <h2>
                            Mindful Movement <span class="badge bg-secondary rounded-pill">Yoga</span>

                        </h2>
                        <p>
                            Many of us are reluctant to exercise because it involves discomfort or strain, or requires special equipment or others to work out with, or going to a special place to do it. If this has been the case for you, then mindful hatha yoga may be just the practice you have been waiting for.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The word ‘yoga’ means ‘yoke’ in Sanskrit, and implies a harnessing together and a unifying of body and mind.  Yoga is a form of meditation, and when done regularly, is a mind and body discipline for people who wish to move towards greater levels of health.
                        </p>
                        <p>

                            Hatha yoga consists of postures done mindfully and with awareness of breathing. They are easily learned and have dramatic effects if practised regularly. The ones we are doing are extremely gentle.  Regular practise will increase your musculoskeletal flexibility, strength, and balance, as well as help you to entre states of deep relaxation and awareness.  Many people experience a greater serenity about life in general, improved circulation, a firmer, trimer figure, and less illness as a result.
                        </p>
                        <p>

                            In practising yoga, you are advised to practice in the same way that you do when meditating; namely, maintaining moment by moment awareness, and not striving to get somewhere, just allowing yourself to be as you are, and letting go of any judging of yourself.   Move slowly and consciously.  Mindful yoga involves exploring your limits but not pushing beyond them.  Instead, you play with dwelling at the boundary and breathe. This requires honouring your body and the ‘messages’ it gives you about when to stop and when to avoid doing a posture, because of your particular condition.
                        </p>
                        <p>

                            Standing yoga requires no special equipment and can be done almost anywhere.  You can learn it from video recordings, and obtain ideas for postures from yoga books.  Experiment mindfully!  Lying down yoga requires a mat and enough space to stretch your arms up and out. Emphasis is on mindfulness and approaching one’s current limits with gentleness.  We are learning to dwell at the boundary without overstepping and investigating what is sensitive and wise, moment to moment.  Avoid any postures they feel would cause them injury or a setback and, to experiment with caution and care when in doubt.
                        </p>
                        <p>

                            If at all possible attend a class with a qualified hatha yoga teacher who can correct your positioning and support you to find alternative or more friendly postures; for example, if you have an injury or experience discomfort in a particular part of your body.

                        </p>

                        <h2>
                            Mindful Movement <span class="badge bg-secondary rounded-pill">Qigong</span>

                        </h2>
                        <p>
                            Qigong is from an ancient Chinese system of movement for health.  The practice consists of a simple series of repeated movements, aimed at utilising the mind with the body, and increasing health in both body and mind.  This is done by gently working on the different systems and organs of the body, and by freeing energy to flow throughout the body, and into our systems from the earth below us and the air around us, nourishing and clearing or minds and bodies.  It is important to bring as full as an awareness as possible to the sensations and movements in your body while doing these exercises, including awareness of breathing.
                        </p>
                        <p>

                            Many of the movements will be done standing up, but can also be adapted to a sitting position, and some can be done lying down.  For this practice, it is helpful to keep the body loose while moving – softening the joints, and imagining energy flowing all around the body.  Only do each exercise the number of times that feels comfortable for you. Listen to your body and be sensitive to how far your body wants to go, and stop when it signals you to do so.  It is fine to simply imagine yourself doing the movements.  Most importantly, be mindful of how your body is feeling right now, and do these movements in a gentle way that respects your body’s current limits.
                        </p>

                        <h2>
                            Mindful Movement <span class="badge bg-secondary rounded-pill">Walking</span>
                        </h2>
                        <p>
                            One simple way of bringing awareness into your daily life is to practice walking meditation.  As you might guess, this means bring your attention to the actual experience of walking as you are doing it.  It means simply walking and experiencing your body walking.
                        </p>
                        <p>

                            One of the things that you find out when you have been practising mindfulness for a while is that  nothing is quiet as simple as it appears.   This is as true for walking as it is for anything else.  For one thing, we carry our mind with us when we walk, so we are usually absorbed in our own thoughts to one extent or another. We are hardly ever just walking, even when we are ‘just going for a walk.’
                        </p>
                        <p>

                            Walking meditation involves intentionally attending to the experience of walking itself. It involves focusing on the sensations in your feet or your legs or, alternatively, feeling your whole body moving.  You can also integrate awareness of your breathing with the experience of walking.
                        </p>
                        <p>

                            We begin by placing our attention and becoming fully aware as one foot contacts the ground, as the weight shifts on to it, as the other foot lifts and moves ahead and then comes down to make contact with the ground in its turn.  As with all the other methods we have been exploring, when the mind wanders away from the feet or the legs or the feeling of the body walking, we simply bring it back when we become aware that it has wandered.  To deepen our concentration, we do not look around at the sights, but keep our gaze focused in front of us.  There is no need to look at our feet, they know how to walk.  It is an internal observation that is being cultivated, just exploring the felt sensations of walking, nothing more.
                        </p>
                        <p>

                            When we practise walking meditation, we are not trying to get anywhere.  It is sufficient just to be with each step, realising that you are just where you are.  The intention is to be there completely. This does not mean that your mind will go along with your intention just to be with each step for very long without a concerted effort to keep it focused. You might soon condemn the whole exercise, calling it stupid, useless, idiotic.  Alternatively, your mind might start to play games; becoming distracted by the pace, by balancing, or have you looking around or thinking of other things.  As your mindfulness grows stronger, you will become more aware of this activity, and return your attention to the feet, legs and body.  It is a good idea to start with awareness of the feet and legs and practise that for a while, then, when your concentration is stronger, you can expand the field of awareness to include a sense of your whole body walking.
                        </p>
                        <p>

                            You can practise mindful walking at any pace.  We sometimes do it very slowly, so that one step might take a minute.  This allows you to really be with each movement from moment to moment.  We also practise it at a more natural pace.  You can practise being aware even when moving quickly; you will find that you will not be able to be with each step so easily, but you can shift your awareness instead to a sense of your body as a whole moving through space.  So even rushing, you can be mindful, if you remember to engage.
                        </p>
                        <p>

                            There are probably circumstances of one kind or another in your life in which you have to be walking.  These can be wonderful occasions to bring awareness to your walking and thereby transform it from a dull, mostly unconscious chore into something rich and nurturing.  So often, when we have routine errands to do, we feel impelled to rush from one to the next until we get them all done.  This can be exhausting, even depressing, because of the monotony of what we are doing, or if the places we go are the same of places where we find ourselves all the time.  The mind craves something new.  If we bring our awareness to our walking during these routine tasks, it will short-circuit the automatic pilot mode and make our routine experiences more vivid and actually more interesting, and leave us calmer and less exhausted at the end.
                        </p>
                        <p>

                            In summary, any time you find yourself walking is a good time to practise mindfulness of walking.  Sometimes it is good to find an isolated spot and do it formally as well, back and forth, step by step, moment by moment, walking gently on the earth, in step with your life, being exactly where you are.

                        </p>



