                        <h2>
                            Home Practice Following Week 3
                        </h2>
                        <p>
                            1. On alternate days do the BODY SCAN practice, and the MINDFUL MOVEMENT practice OR the WALKING MEDITATION.

                            The point of movement is to provide a direct way to connect with the body. The body is a place where the emotions often get expressed, under the surface and without our awareness. Thoughts and emotions also affect our bodies. Working with our bodies directly gives us a place to experience more of ourselves, and to connect our experience of body, feelings and thoughts.  The movements activate the body and mind, provide a direct way to connect with awareness of the body, and can dispel tiredness.

                            Record any reactions on your record form if you wish to.

                            If you have any back problems or other health issues that may cause difficulties, make your own decision as to which (if any) of these exercises to do, take good care of your body. You can make a mindfulness practise out of any movements you do, by bringing full attention to them.

                        </p>

                        <p>
                            2. At a different time practice 10-15 minutes of MINDFULNESS OF BREATHING each day.  Record your reaction on the record form if you wish.

                        </p>

                        <p>
                            3. Complete the UNPLEASANT EXPERIENCES DIARY (one entry per day). This is an opportunity to become really aware of the thoughts, feelings and body sensations that are around during an unpleasant event each day at the time they are occurring.  Notice and record the detail of the experience as soon as you can; for example, put the actual words or images that thoughts came in, and the precise nature and location of bodily sensations.

                            <ul>
                                <li>What are the unpleasant events that ‘pull you off centre’, or ‘get you down’ (not matter how big or small)?</li>
                                <li>What do you not like looking at?</li>
                                <li>Notice when you move into ‘automatic pilot’. Under what circumstances does this occur?</li>
                            </ul>

                            Hare in your awareness an intention to ‘capture’ the moments of your day.

                        </p>

